<p class="guide-meta">&#128197; Last reviewed: June 2026 &nbsp;&middot;&nbsp; HealthCalculation Editorial Team</p>
<p class="guide-intro">Counting calories gets you into the right energy range. Tracking macros lets you control <em>what happens to your body</em> within that range — whether you preserve muscle while cutting, build lean mass while bulking, or simply feel better and perform better. This guide walks you through the calculation from TDEE to daily gram targets.</p>

<h2>Step 1 — Find Your TDEE</h2>
<p>Your <strong>Total Daily Energy Expenditure (TDEE)</strong> is the number of calories you burn per day including activity. All macro calculations start here. Use the Mifflin-St Jeor equation with an activity multiplier:</p>

<table class="data-table">
  <thead>
    <tr><th>Activity Level</th><th>Multiplier</th><th>Description</th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td>Sedentary</td><td>× 1.2</td><td>Desk job, little to no exercise</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Lightly active</td><td>× 1.375</td><td>Light exercise 1–3 days/week</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Moderately active</td><td>× 1.55</td><td>Moderate exercise 3–5 days/week</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Very active</td><td>× 1.725</td><td>Hard exercise 6–7 days/week</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Extra active</td><td>× 1.9</td><td>Physical job + hard training daily</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<h2>Step 2 — Set Your Calorie Target by Goal</h2>
<p>Adjust TDEE based on your goal. These are evidence-based ranges that balance results with sustainability:</p>

<table class="data-table">
  <thead>
    <tr><th>Goal</th><th>Calorie Adjustment</th><th>Expected Rate</th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td>Aggressive fat loss</td><td>TDEE − 500 kcal</td><td>~0.5 kg / week</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Moderate fat loss</td><td>TDEE − 300 kcal</td><td>~0.3 kg / week</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Maintenance / recomp</td><td>TDEE ± 0</td><td>Fat loss + muscle gain (slow)</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Lean bulk</td><td>TDEE + 200 kcal</td><td>~0.2 kg / week muscle</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Moderate bulk</td><td>TDEE + 400 kcal</td><td>~0.3–0.4 kg / week</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<h2>Step 3 — Choose Your Macro Ratio</h2>
<p>Macro ratios are expressed as percentages of total calories. These are the most commonly used evidence-based splits:</p>

<table class="data-table">
  <thead>
    <tr><th>Goal</th><th>Protein</th><th>Carbs</th><th>Fat</th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td>Fat loss (cutting)</td><td>40%</td><td>35%</td><td>25%</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Maintenance</td><td>30%</td><td>40%</td><td>30%</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Muscle gain (bulking)</td><td>30%</td><td>45%</td><td>25%</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Low-carb / keto</td><td>30%</td><td>10%</td><td>60%</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Endurance athlete</td><td>20%</td><td>55%</td><td>25%</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<h2>Step 4 — Convert to Grams</h2>
<p>Each macronutrient has a fixed calorie density. Use these to convert from calories to grams:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Protein:</strong> 4 kcal per gram → divide protein calories by 4</li>
  <li><strong>Carbohydrates:</strong> 4 kcal per gram → divide carb calories by 4</li>
  <li><strong>Fat:</strong> 9 kcal per gram → divide fat calories by 9</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>Example:</strong> TDEE 2,200 kcal, cutting goal (−300 kcal = 1,900 kcal), 40/35/25 split:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Protein: 1,900 × 0.40 ÷ 4 = <strong>190 g</strong></li>
  <li>Carbs: 1,900 × 0.35 ÷ 4 = <strong>166 g</strong></li>
  <li>Fat: 1,900 × 0.25 ÷ 9 = <strong>53 g</strong></li>
</ul>

<h2>Macro Targets at Common Calorie Levels</h2>
<p>Quick-reference table using a 40/35/25 split (cutting) at popular calorie targets:</p>

<table class="data-table">
  <thead>
    <tr><th>Daily Calories</th><th>Protein (g)</th><th>Carbs (g)</th><th>Fat (g)</th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td>1,400 kcal</td><td>140</td><td>123</td><td>39</td></tr>
    <tr><td>1,600 kcal</td><td>160</td><td>140</td><td>44</td></tr>
    <tr><td>1,800 kcal</td><td>180</td><td>158</td><td>50</td></tr>
    <tr><td>2,000 kcal</td><td>200</td><td>175</td><td>56</td></tr>
    <tr><td>2,200 kcal</td><td>220</td><td>193</td><td>61</td></tr>
    <tr><td>2,500 kcal</td><td>250</td><td>219</td><td>69</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<h2>The Most Important Macro: Protein</h2>
<p>If you only track one macro, make it protein. Research consistently shows that adequate protein intake:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Preserves lean muscle mass during a caloric deficit</li>
  <li>Has the highest thermic effect of food (20–30% of calories burned in digestion)</li>
  <li>Increases satiety more than carbs or fat, reducing total calorie intake</li>
  <li>Supports muscle protein synthesis when combined with resistance training</li>
</ul>
<p>The ISSN recommends <strong>1.6–2.2 g per kg of body weight</strong> for active individuals. Set protein first, then fill remaining calories with carbs and fat to your preference.</p>

<h2>Common Macro Mistakes</h2>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Setting protein too low</strong> — the most common error; results in muscle loss during cutting</li>
  <li><strong>Ignoring calorie total</strong> — clean macros at the wrong calorie level will not produce results</li>
  <li><strong>Cutting carbs to near-zero</strong> without a specific reason — impairs training performance and recovery</li>
  <li><strong>Not adjusting as weight changes</strong> — recalculate every 4–6 weeks as body weight and TDEE shift</li>
  <li><strong>Tracking nutrition apps inaccurately</strong> — use a food scale; volume estimates are often 20–30% off</li>
</ul>

